{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians --> | name = The Pizza Underground | image = The Pizza Underground.jpg | landscape = yes | caption = Chicago 2014 | background = group_or_band | origin = [[New York City]] | genre = {{hlist|[[Comedy rock]]|[[anti-folk]]}} | years_active = {{start date|2013}}–present | associated_acts = | website = {{URL|http://thepizzaunderground.tumblr.com/}} | current_members = * [[Macaulay Culkin]] * [[Corey McCracklins]] * Matt Colbourn * [[Phoebe Kreutz]] * Deenah Vollmer * Austin Kilham | instruments = {{hlist|Guitar|glockenspiel|drums|tambourine|kazoo|pizza box}} }}
'''The Pizza Underground''' was an American [[Comedy music|comedy]] [[Rock music|rock]] band based in [[New York City]]. Mainly [[Parody music|parodying]] songs by [[the Velvet Underground]] with [[pizza]]-themed song names and lyrics, the group consisted of former [[child actor]] [[Macaulay Culkin]] ([[kazoo]], [[percussion]] and vocals) along with Matt Colbourn (guitar, vocals), [[Phoebe Kreutz]] ([[glockenspiel]], vocals), Deenah Vollmer ([[pizza box]], vocals) and Austin Kilham ([[tambourine]], vocals).<ref name=pitchfork>{{cite web|last=Pelly|first=Jenn|title=Listen: Macaulay Culkin Has a Pizza-Themed Velvet Underground Cover Band, The Pizza Underground|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/53269-listen-macaulay-culkin-has-a-pizza-themed-velvet-underground-cover-band-the-pizza-underground/|work=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=jezebel>{{cite web|last=Beck|first=Laura|title=Macaulay Culkin Has a Pizza-Themed Velvet Underground Cover Band|url=http://jezebel.com/macaulay-culkin-has-a-pizza-themed-velvet-underground-c-1479308740|work=[[Jezebel]]|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=rollingstone>{{cite web|last=Ayers|first=Mike|title=Inside Macaulay Culkin's Pizza Underground Sessions|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/inside-macaulay-culkins-pizza-underground-sessions-20131212|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> Because of the theme, the band gave out boxed pizzas to people who attended their live performances.
==History==
Deenah Vollmer, the group's "pizza box" percussionist, said the idea for the Pizza Underground began as a joke in 2012.<ref name=philly>{{cite web|last=Amorosi|first=A.D.|title=Season of tributes to Lou Reed - including Macaulay Culkin's band Pizza Underground Read|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/music/20140123_Macaulay_Culkin_s_Pizza_Underground_brings_Velvet_tribute_to_PhilaMOCA.html|work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]|publisher=philly.com|accessdate=23 January 2014}}{{dead link|date=January 2017}}</ref> "We soon realized you can replace most any word with slice or cheese," she told ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. [[Glockenspiel]] player Phoebe Kreutz stated they believed the Velvet Underground songs were written about pizza, but had to be reworded to accommodate the "standards of their day."<ref name=philly />
On November 11, 2013, the group recorded a live demo at [[Macaulay Culkin]]'s house.<ref name=pitchfork /> That same month they performed a [[Lou Reed]] tribute show at the Sidewalk Cafe in the [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]].<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|last=Michaels|first=Sean|title=Macaulay Culkin forms pizza-themed Velvet Underground tribute band|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/dec/09/macaulay-culkin-pizza-velvet-underground|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> In December, a viral video of Culkin eating a cheese pizza was uploaded to [[YouTube]]. He was parodying [[Andy Warhol]] consuming a [[Burger King Whopper]] in [[Jørgen Leth]]'s documentary ''66 Scenes from America''.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9pzm1lQX0qU</ref> Culkin was promoting the debut of the Pizza Underground.<ref>Luling, Todd Van, December 27, 2013 [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/27/pizza-news-2013_n_4462102.html 'The 34 greatest moments in pizza history from 2013'], retrieved December 27, 2013</ref>
The group released its first music video in January 2014, parodying various Velvet Underground songs such as "All Pizza Parties" ("[[All Tomorrow's Parties]]"), "Pizza Gal" ("[[Femme Fatale (The Velvet Underground song)|Femme Fatale]]") and "Take a Bite of the Wild Slice" ([[Lou Reed]]'s "[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]").<ref name=huffpost>{{cite web|last=Kristobak|first=Ryan|title=Macaulay Culkin Band Pizza Underground's First Music Video Is Full Of Pizza Faces|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/01/07/macaulay-culkin-pizza-band-video_n_4556771.html|work=[[Huffington Post]]|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> The video featured the group performing on a bed of pizza boxes, surrounded by pizza checkered walls, with members of the group wearing slices of pizza as masks.<ref name=daily_news>{{cite web|last=Eby|first=Margaret|title=Macaulay Culkin's Pizza Underground band debuts saucy music video|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/macauley-culkin-pizza-underground-band-debuts-video-article-1.1569761|work=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]]|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref> Also in 2014, the cassette of the demo was released by Bitter Melody Records<ref>Bitter Melody Records, [http://bittermelodyrecords.limitedrun.com/about About Bitter Melody Records]. Retrieved February 15, 2016.</ref> on yellow, white, and red cassettes.<ref name=USAToday>{{cite web|last=Matheson|first=Whitney|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/popcandy/2014/01/27/macaulay-culkin-pizza-underground/4943021/|title=Pop Candy: Hear a demo from Macaulay Culkin on Cassette|date= January 27, 2014|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=February 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>Bitter Melody Records, [http://bittermelodyrecords.limitedrun.com/products/524334-the-pizza-underground-demo-tape-featuring-macaulay-culkin Particulars of Pizza Underground Demo Cassette Release]. Retrieved February 15, 2016.</ref> An 18-show North American tour entitled ''Fresh to Your Door'' took place that same year.<ref name=daily_news />
In May 2014, the band was [[booing|booed]] off the stage at the Rock City venue in [[Nottingham]], England, while performing at the [[Dot to Dot Festival]]. A spectator later complained that the parody group were making a "mockery of one of the greatest bands of all time".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-27585631|title=Macaulay Culkin booed off stage in Nottingham|date= May 27, 2014|work=[[BBC News]]|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref> The band quit playing within 15 minutes, and in response to having pints of beers thrown at the band, [[frontman]] Macaulay Culkin exclaimed to the crowd, "why are you throwing those? ...I'd rather drink them!"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/10857509/Macaulay-Culkins-band-booed-off-in-Nottingham.html|title=Macaulay Culkin's band booed off in Nottingham|date= May 27, 2014|work=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|accessdate=May 27, 2014}}</ref>
The initial cassette release was followed by ''Live at Chop Suey'', also on Bitter Melody Records,<ref>Bitter Melody Records, [http://bittermelodyrecords.limitedrun.com/products/535312-pizza-underground-live-at-chop-suey-cassette Particulars of ''Live at Chop Suey'']. Retrieved February 15, 2016.</ref> recorded at the Chop Suey<ref>[http://chopsuey.com/generalinfo/ Particulars of Chop Suey, Seattle]. Retrieved February 15, 2016.</ref> in [[Seattle, Washington]].
